PCA scores returns the estimation of Pca based on the eigenvalues. I am going to analyze first three components. Since first three explains only 52%, we may not obtain a clear picture

#adding first two columns to pca&scores
pca_score_with_Instance <- cbind(Musk1$V1,Musk1$V2,pca$scores)
pca_score_with_Instance <- as.data.frame(pca_score_with_Instance)

plot(pca_score_with_Instance[,3:4],col = pca_score_with_Instance$V1+2,  xlab = "Component 1", ylab = "Component 2", main = "PCA Results")
legend("bottomright",cex = 0.55, legend = c("0", "1"),fill = 2:3)

The figure above shows PCA scores of two component. In middle part (Component 1 (0,5),Component 2(0,-10)) we mostly see Musks, In the bottom sides we observe Nonmasks but is not possible to generate a conclusion from this figure. Because most of the data is at top left and top right and they are mixed. At this point we cannot say that the assumption of the instance labels’ being as the same as bag labels is accurate. However first two component explains only 45% of variation. I am going to add component 3 to the figure.

——————————-TASK 2.2—————————–

I will add noise between minpixel and maxpixel/10.

#a)
# Adding Noise 

minPixel = min(cat_image)
maxPixel_over_ten = max(cat_image)/10

Noisy_Cat<-array(0,dim = c(256,256,3))
for(i in 1:3){
for(k in 1:256){
for(l in 1:256){
  random_number<- 1 - runif(1, min = minPixel, max = maxPixel_over_ten)
 Noisy_Cat[k,l,i]<-cat_image[k,l,i]*random_number
}}}


#Display noisy cat image
plot(1:256 ,type='n',main = "Noisy_Cat Image")
rasterImage(Noisy_Cat,0,0,256,256,angle = 0,interpolate = F)

This 256x256x3 vectors. I will assign last two component zeros and will find blue, red and green images

#b)
#Creating blue channel images by assigning others to zero
Noisy_Cat_b<-Noisy_Cat
Noisy_Cat_b[,,1]=0
Noisy_Cat_b[,,2]=0
#Creating red channel images by assigning others to zero
Noisy_Cat_r<-Noisy_Cat
Noisy_Cat_r[,,2]=0
Noisy_Cat_r[,,3]=0
#Creating green channel images by assigning others to zero
Noisy_Cat_g<-Noisy_Cat
Noisy_Cat_g[,,1]=0
Noisy_Cat_g[,,3]=0

In order to reconstruct the images I am going to use pca score parameters.pca$scores[,1] shows the score calculated based on the first pca component. However to use the scores, we have to scale it before. Otherwise I could get values out of [0,1]
————–TASK 2.3.B ———————–

#score vector is 232x1 vector. After scaling it I am forming the Component_1 matrix
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
Component_1 <- (noisy_pca$scores[,1] - min(noisy_pca$scores[,1]))/(max(noisy_pca$scores[,1])-min(noisy_pca$scores[,1]))
plot(1:232,1:232, ann = TRUE,col=0, main = "25x25 Patches - Comp 1 Scores", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(matrix(Component_1, 232, byrow=TRUE),0,0,232,232)

Component_2 <- (noisy_pca$scores[,2] - min(noisy_pca$scores[,2]))/(max(noisy_pca$scores[,2])-min(noisy_pca$scores[,2]))
plot(1:232,1:232, ann = TRUE,col=0, main = "25x25 Patches - Comp 2 Scores", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(matrix(Component_2, 232, byrow=TRUE),0,0,232,232)

Component_3 <- (noisy_pca$scores[,3] - min(noisy_pca$scores[,3]))/(max(noisy_pca$scores[,3])-min(noisy_pca$scores[,3]))
plot(1:232,1:232, ann = TRUE,col=0, main = "25x25 Patches - Comp 3 Scores", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(matrix(Component_3, 232, byrow=TRUE),0,0,232,232)

Since first component explains the highest variance, it is the best represenatation.

#scaling process for the first three component. There 25 components in total.
eigen1 <- matrix((noisy_pca$loadings[,1 ]-min(noisy_pca$loadings[,1 ]))/(max(noisy_pca$loadings[,1 ])-min(noisy_pca$loadings[,1 ])),25,byrow=TRUE)

We see almost uniform distribution in Eigen1. In Eigen2 bottom part has higher values and in Eigen3 right part has higher values. Here eigen values corresponds to weight of patches. Differences in values shows different weight of patches. For example in the third chart, patches in the right part have higher weight compared to patcesh in the left side.Therefore we expect to see better representation in Eigen1 compared to others and that was what happened in the previous part.
